Imagine someone who chooses to sacrifice his or her own happiness in order to help others, and claims that this is the best sort of life to live. Would the existence of such a person be a problem for hedonism? (reading discussion)
3. No. 
People make mistakes when connecting instrumental to intrinsic value. A person sacrificing happiness to help others either takes immense pleasure in helping others, or they are just outright mistaken about how helping others will make themselves happy.

You can also imagine someone accidentally pulling a trigger to kill their own squadmate in the heat of battle. Did he consciously want the person to be shot at that time? yes. but the choice was misinformed because he wouldn't have pulled the trigger had he known the enemy was in fact your friend.

Similarly, if you inform the person who sacrifices their happiness to help others, I think they would stop.

