murderous people running around hardly seems like the best thing (reading 2.2)
I invite you to think about a universe with only 2 people. Both of them wanting to murder each other, but neither wanting to actually get killed.

This example illustrates that it is not possible for any system to achieve what "seems like the best thing" because the best thing is if each of them both got to kill each other and also somehow didnt die (which is a contradiction).

The scope of the problem intuitively is "what is best for the society", which is distinct from what hedonism addresses which is "what is best for one person"

Any system would have to trade something off, either the person's freedom to murder, or the person's desires to live. I argue that hedonism does not resolve this as the intuitive best solution, but it's the best any theory can do.

False happiness (reading 2.3)
Living in a perfect lie is the same as living in a perfect world. I think the point is that you are a third person who can tell the difference. Remember hedonism appeals to PERSONAL feelings. The two women in their fake/real marriages wouldn't possibly know their lives were switched.

You, as an outsider, might say that the fake one looks worse. but that's you projecting your thoughts on what's good for them. Your empathy is misled because you are thinking "she WOULD be sad if she knew it was fake", which, by premise, she wouldn't.

